textDisplay:
"Expats" and immigrants aren't exactly the same thing and have pretty specific connotations (that aren't necessarily to do with being white). Expats consider themselves 100% their nationality of origin, rarely seek citizenship unless obliged and their goal in moving abroad is not necessarily one of integration nor contribution, but rather leisure. They tend to be retired or semi-retired and fairly wealthy, although many choose countries where their wealth will stretch even further, as well as not bringing children. Their goal is to live a permanent vacation in these countries - popular expat destination countries will usually have several "clubs" for residents of the same original nationality to do tours and other activities on a regular basis. Generally speaking, these people do not bring skills or services but they do inject a bunch of foreign money into the local economy on a permanent basis. You can't really directly compare being an immigrant to being an expat - one implies integration, settlement, working, new life, family etc.. while the other implies restaurants, snorkelling and wine tours. I get that you want to take this opportunity to take a shot at whitey as is so customary these days, but I think in this case they simply used two different words with two different connotations, grouped under a single statistic. I am a British-born man who lives and works abroad with his wife from that country, and I most definitely consider myself an immigrant whilst maintaining that the word expatriate describes a different situation to my own.

I think the term definitely has economic implications (you need to be rich enough to sustain yourself abroad without working) but making it racial is less relevant, especially in this context. Not only are there plenty of occasions both contemporary and historical where ethnically white immigrants are referred to as just that (immigrants), but I would also be quite surprised to learn that most of the rich, unemployed playboys with houses in the giant resort-city of Dubai were white.

textDisplay:
I just came back from Dubai last week from a 12 days holiday trip with my fiancée. We wanted to find a place remotely close to us (Switzerland), with sun and beach, without being too expensive flight-wise.

So we went to Dubai. Without expectations. It's never been on our list of "To go to" places.

What I can say about the city is that it's really impressive, massive, clean and secure. Of course, it is all that at the places we stayed at (Marina and Downtown). We're aware of the hidden misery happening behind curtains.

Aside from the craziness of the buildings, skylines and man-made islands, the city struck us as tasteless, soulless, fake, oddly and hypocritically prude (given the main religion and the mix with barely dressed men and women strolling the streets) and trying way too hard.

I mean, it was fun, we ate well, we enjoyed the beach and the sun. But that's pretty much it... It's a city built for business, entertaining tourists and laundring money.

I kind of got the feeling that the people building the city there think that throwing all the money in the world to build a town with modern utilities, massive roads and enormous malls (The Dubai Mall OMG) suffice to create a megalopole. But they forgot what makes a city... well... a city: its inhabitants. The people. As I said, as people are there for business or for holidays, there's no sense of being in an inhabited city, with history, with art, with culture.

Something else totally baffled me... Witnessing full burqa women and their husbands walking alongside full "plastic-surgery-short-skirt-high-heels-boobs-out" bimbos.

Also, the streets are clearly built for cars. Don't think you're in NYC, Paris, Tokyo, Zürich or London where you can spend hours walking down the streets, enjoying the city by foot. I guess that's why almost every massive buildings there have a gym, a pool and a 24/7 market store, so you don't need to leave your building. And if you do, it's by cab that you get to your destination anyway... You can go enjoy a walk in the streets if it's been planned for you to do so. Otherwise, it's a car city.

Another thing: the number of workers being 3 or 4 doing the job of one person... But not only that, but having all modern facilities, with automatic doors you need to use your ticket to pass through, yet having those doors off so a guy can scan your ticket. Instead of the maching he's standing in front of. But instead of being just one guy, it's 3.

I don't know... Maybe I'm too much of an arrogant European (especially since I'm French, double the arrogance I guess then), but Dubai is cool for a one-time holiday session only in my book. It's clearly just a façade though, a beautiful car with no engine in it.

textDisplay: Dubai sucks. And lastly, the city is honestly devoid of culture and spirit. My favorite part of the city was actually old Dubai, because that’s where the authenticity of the ME culture shines the most, despite it being a relatively “unappealing” place to go to, especially when compared to the bling of the newer city. I went there on a trip a few years back, and while I did enjoy the trip overall, and am thankful that I have at least experienced what Dubai is like, I do not plan on going there again

If he built the tallest building in the world he'd know that plumbing is a huge issue in tall buildings. And all the "poop trucks" have their own lane and it does NOT affect traffic. Also "poop trucks" haven't existed in 7 years. (Proves my point of 0 research)

"Why not build the palm in the desert?" Simply because its much cooler and will attract more tourists and boost the economy

At least the workers have a place to live that isn't as bad as your basement. In their home countries they would be living on the streets.

I hope I have enlightened everyone reading this. Stuff on the internet may be true but its not always completely true.

textDisplay: I'm an Indian living in Dubai and I have to agree with some parts in the video but also disagree because it's honestly not at all bad, at least to me. I love Dubai, I grew up here and for me this city has felt more like a home than my own country. It's true that the richer you are, the better your life here would be. You can also pointedly see the difference in how people from different countries are paid differently for the same job. Honestly if you're not earning well, Dubai is not for you. I also have to say that Dubai is still a developing city; it's very easy to forget that fact when you see all the luxury but there're dark and developing sides here as well.

This video is very misleading. I have lived in Dubai all my life, and like everywhere else in the world, there will always be a contrast between classes.
There is no place in the world that doesn't have a mix of White Collar and Blue Collar working class.

For example, people love New York till they are in Manhattan. But you ask someone to spend their entire New York holiday in the Bronx, they would then think that New York too is "A Parody of the 21st century".


I can keep my hand on my heart and say that Dubai is one of the best places in the world. It makes you feel safe and gives you a sense of security. Nowhere else will you see such rapid growth.

And for God's sake, do not forget that this entire country was just a desert just 50 years ago. If you can't appreciate the hardwork and the good things about this country, atleast don't bash it. This country has achieved more in 50 years than most achieve in centuries.

Dubai municipality has planned every restaurants like that. On the other hand all residential and commercial buildings have two pipeline connection...sewage and sullage.They take out water from one of them and after process it gets discharged in plants all over dubai automatically. And waste from sewage and sullage pipelines goes to the again their plants to make energy...you are just pooping and they make energy from it. This is insane idea 😂. I've never seen a single area or corner which is not cleaned. Cleaners collect garbage every 2 hous from the streets. Dustbins are getting changed every week(they wash it in their warehouses so don't look filthy on streets). They burn down every other garbage except biological waste. Plastics get shredded and idk what happens to them next buy they may have plans about it too. So conclusion is...dubai is not hallucination, they built mind-blowing city in a fckin dessert, have massive green parks in every areas...They have planned it and have built it all.

textDisplay:
I have been big fan of grid street systems of old American cities, which are more walkable and accepting of small business. Also you can add different types of housing such as low rise apartments, single family residences, or row housing.

I also think a lot of this has to do with the style in which we build modern buildings, most are covered in either glass, steel, plastics, or some other nefarious (and sometimes rare) material such as particle board.

What we should really do is go back to building attractive yet functional buildings that actually use natural materials, or even reusing salvaged materials such as wood, stone and brick which are more likely now to be tossed into a landfill.

You mentioned public transit. There was a time in my home state when we had interurban railroads running across the state of Iowa. One line ran from Des Moines to Ames, while another connected Cedar Falls/Waterloo, Cedar Rapids, and Iowa City in one large line. Des Moines and most of my states major cities had electric street cars (which are cleaner than buses btw). Instead of keeping the electric street cars, investors would by up private held street car companies, disband the service, and put busses in their place. San Francisco is an example of a city where the street car system was municipally controlled and ran, hence why they still have this reliable and environmentally friendly service.

textDisplay: Superb video. But Brecht is wrong. Alexander did not conquer India. He only made it to the northwest part of the Indian subcontinent, the area that is Pakistan today. He was defeated by the Indian king Porus and the Greeks made a humiliating exit from India. Harried by partisans and fiercely opposed by local kingdoms, his entire cavalry plus a significant portion of the Greek infantry was destroyed in India. Alexander was injured in the battle with the Mallian republic and that arrow wound in the lung ultimately led to his death. The Greeks did win some early battles against small Indian kingdoms but he certainly didn't conquer India.
textOriginal: Superb video. But Brecht is wrong. Alexander did not conquer India. He only made it to the northwest part of the Indian subcontinent, the area that is Pakistan today. He was defeated by the Indian king Porus and the Greeks made a humiliating exit from India. textDisplay: Could not agree with you more, having worked in Civil Engineering your comments on what has been built there is spot on. Out of pure curiosity I chose to stop over for two days and because of my flight in and out was at two airports which meant I saw a lot of their traffic infrastructure. I went up up the Shard and visited the Dubai Islands and was not impressed at all,  just 'monstrocities'. I recall seeing a garderner at the bottom of the Shard who was spaying something onto the flowers, getting clser I though it was some form of weed spray but then then realize it was paint - I could not believe my eyes and I immdiately thoughtt of Alice in Wonderland the roses being painted red. On my flight onwards to Japan I got talking to a German resident who was a Consulting Engineer on the Shard and other projects in Dubai, having both (albeit mine far more limited) I was surprise at how critical he was by effectively covering nearly all the points you made. I asked what changed him and why, he smiled sarconically and said "Simple, money and knowing I can retire to a place in way like Dubai"

textDisplay: Great video and noble mission, but stones you throw at the slang abbreviation “expat” is a little out of order. First, expat is short slang for expatriate, which is a VERY old word that can be traced back to old Latin. There are also very subtle but distinct differences in the meaning, expatriate is a person that moves out or even gives up citizenship of their native country TEMPORARILY. Immigrant is PERMANENTLY. Migrant is one that continuously travels through other countries for work. Thus, your claim that the word is made up by white people comes across as mostly just disdain and subtle racism towards white people. Especially when you actually know the history of the word and don’t buy all the bs trend today of being racist to whites acting like it’s some more noble and funny approach. Everything else is great, but that jab, while funny to many, is actually cloaked racism and prejudice or perhaps vindictive attitude for wealthy white folks. Which frankly is no better than the racism some of those types give others. If you make a claim, make sure it’s correct, the jest is tainted with your face baiting to. Otherwise great video.

textDisplay: An immigrant is someone who gives up their original citizenship to obtain a new one in the new country, therefore their move is somewhat permanent. Neither are bad, it's just a way to differentiate between two subtly different sets of circumstances

textDisplay:
I met a traveller from an antique land,
Who said—“Two vast and trunkless legs of stone
Stand in the desert. . . . Near them, on the sand,
Half sunk a shattered visage lies, whose frown,
And wrinkled lip, and sneer of cold command,
Tell that its sculptor well those passions read
Which yet survive, stamped on these lifeless things,
The hand that mocked them, and the heart that fed;
And on the pedestal, these words appear:
My name is Ozymandias, King of Kings;
Look on my Works, ye Mighty, and despair!
Nothing beside remains. Round the decay
Of that colossal Wreck, boundless and bare
The lone and level sands stretch far away.”
textOriginal:
I met a traveller from an antique land,
Who said—“Two vast and trunkless legs of stone
Stand in the desert. . . . Near them, on the sand,
Half sunk a shattered visage lies, whose frown,
And wrinkled lip, and sneer of cold command,
Tell that its sculptor well those passions read
Which yet survive, stamped on these lifeless things,
The hand that mocked them, and the heart that fed;
And on the pedestal, these words appear:
My name is Ozymandias, King of Kings;
Look on my Works, ye Mighty, and despair!
Nothing beside remains. Round the decay
Of that colossal Wreck, boundless and bare
The lone and level sands stretch far away.”

textDisplay: I haven’t made it that far in the video yet so I’m not sure if you elaborated on it yet but the community system is a fucking mess. Imagine you are living in a town with around 500 people. Now Imagine your friend lives in another town of the same size that is a 5 minute cycle away. Now insert a fucking highway in between those towns so that the only possible way to get to that town without being run over by a car is by a car itself. This is Dubai, if your friend lives in another “community” than you, god forbid you want to try to walk to them. After living in about 4 communities during my time there, the only ones I would really be able to cycle around to other communities in are motor city (which is actually more of a group of communities with a downtown area modeled after a New York-ish style) and jumeirah islands which has gotten to the point where you have communities inside of communities.

textDisplay:
Expat is not the same as immigrant, and it is very stupid of you to say so. First; expats are specifically those who do not take on permanent residency or similar citizenship changes or additions. This is the biggest difference. Second, expats also include those who do not live permanently in the nation, but rather temporarily. Third, it also includes people who are on strictly temporary work visas, or living in a place temporarily as a part of their normal course of work.

This differs significantly from an immigrant in that; First, an Expat is not implied to have moved to the destination for a better life, but rather as a result of the course of their life, or a specific appreciate for that country's culture or environment. Specifically, the prospect of novel work and opportunity is not a driving factor. Second, an Expat is not moving to the destination because of the prospect of a potential change in citizenship, nationality, or official status within the target nation.

I want to clarify these things because language is extremely important, and chocking up the differences of words to "racism" is fucking pathetic.

Migrant, Immigrant, Emigrant, Expatriate, Exile, and Refugee are all extremely similar words with vast nuance in their use-case and application. To suggest it is racism that most people who are referred to as "expats" are white, is to expose yourself as a racist, or ignorant, as you either don't feel that the "darkies" can be referred to as expats, or never understand the actual semantic differences.

She also had some very graphic horror stories of the conditions in the labourers lived in, since she used to get letters from them as part of her role in HR. Her British company would just trash the letters. Sad to see nothing has changed.
Something that doesn't talked about much is how the place can change you. I've seen fun, optimistic, regular people go there and turn in to sceptical, shallow, racist or weary people, depending on the kind of person they are. And that effect does not wear off even after they return home. The experience seems to fundamentally change you, almost always for the negative.

textDisplay:
“because that word is reserved for brown people.” Nope. Wrong. “Immigrant” has the connotation of “poor” and “seeking opportunity.” In the US, there were generations of WHITE Irish, German, and Italian immigrants, and they were hated by MANY of the white, native-born citizens. Immigrant is NOT a “race” thing. It’s a class thing. “Immigrant” has the connotation of “poor” moving to a rich country. An expat is often the opposite: rich moving to a poor country. Both can be seeking better opportunities to become richer (stretch your retirement account further for expats), but each comes from a different starting place. An immigrant is likely someone moving from the third to the first world, where an expat is coming from the first world. An “immigrant” to Singapore will be poor. An “expat” to Singapore will be at least middle class and probably rich. An “immigrant” is often forced by circumstance to go looking for something better. For expats, it is a voluntary lateral move due to preference not desperation … because it is a CLASS thing, not a race thing primarily…

I liked everything you said before this.

textDisplay: I have been to Dubay several times. Yes I constantly encountered these poor dark-skinned slaves mainly from the south of India, living in shipping containers, uniformed and bussed to their workplaces, to whom all this wonderland of Dubai and all of its pleasures were more out of reach than the Moon. As for the town planning and infrastructure, well, many American cities are not better, in fact - many are worse. As for all this glitter - I think many of us who went through a trauma of growing up in the Communist world have this strange  idea that anything glittery and modern and with skyskrapers equals to the West, i.e. prosperity,  progress, democracy, human rights etc. etc. This notion may have been true in the 1970s or 80s, but it is completely erroneous now, just look at China. Talking about the Arab world, most of the Arab countries are poor and/or unstable, going through civil wars or tremendous political crises. There are very few of Arab countries which are rich and seemingly stable - UAE, Qatar, Oman and a few others. Saudi Arabia  - islamic North Korea - is liberalising a bit in terms of women's rights etc, but politically it is as bad as ever - remember Khashoggi's murder. But even more generally, is there a single Arab/Muslim country in the world where human rights would be respected and justice and rule of law would prevail? Turkey? Nice try, but it failed too after a century of bungled up experiments.

textDisplay:
i went to dubai a few years ago, and ill just say i wasnt very impressed. The only thing that wowed me was the sheer amount skyscrapers, just driving down the big highway its got skyscrpaers each bigger than biggest one in my home city, lining the road on either side for miles and miles.
Other than that, theres kinda bugger all there, I went on a tour of the old town, which was fine, but on our drive back from that to our hotel we were stuck in the worst traffic id ever been in, it took soo long we ended up ditching our ride and just walked. (I wont give the whole story, but at that point i hadnt slept or eaten in about 40 hours, so to say i was miserable is an understatement, and it might have biased my opinion on this city).
One day we drove out to the end of the big palm, and when we got there i was like "wait are we really here?" you cant tell your on the palm, its just like being at any sea side place, it was very disappointing.
Also regarding the supercars the police drive, i didnt see a single one when i was there, and i spoke to a taxi driver about it, he told me that they now use undercover cars, as when people see police they think something is about to go wrong. Whilst this thinking isnt wrong, it definitely makes me think less of them as theyre kinda known for it and i wasnt able to see it. Its a bit of a difference to when I went to either the UK or Ireland (sorry i forget which), and there were just army people patrolling the streets, carrying their SA80 assault rifles, it definitely made me feel more scared like they were preparing for some terrorist attack or something.

Of the 2 nights i spent in Dubai, i didnt like it, it was abnormally expensive, aside from the city theres fuck all there, and im not a huge fan of spending my life in a city, and i dont think ill be going back in a hurry.

textDisplay:
Historically, the Middle East was the heart of the world's finest scholarship, medicine and architecture! It's tragic to think of the wasted potential of Dubai; instead of cutting-edge medical facilities they have a shopping center with an indoor ski slope, for god's sake.
And why duplicate the look of major cities in America when Islamic architecture has produced breathtakingly beautiful structures like Instanbul's Hagia Sophia?
Every point the host makes is a good one, and indicates the major problems that come with fabulous wealth -- wealth that's not backed up by careful planning. I'd love to visit a city celebrating the best a culture has to offer; I refuse to waste my time visiting a duplicate of Los Angeles while knowing it was built on cruelty, worker exploitation and human rights violations!
textOriginal:
Historically, the Middle East was the heart of the world's finest scholarship, medicine and architecture! It's tragic to think of the wasted potential of Dubai; instead of cutting-edge medical facilities they have a shopping center with an indoor ski slope, for god's sake.
And why duplicate the look of major cities in America when Islamic architecture has produced breathtakingly beautiful structures like Instanbul's Hagia Sophia?
Every point the host makes is a good one, and indicates the major problems that come with fabulous wealth -- wealth that's not backed up by careful planning. I'd love to visit a city celebrating the best a culture has to offer; I refuse to waste my time visiting a duplicate of Los Angeles while knowing it was built on cruelty, worker exploitation and human rights violations!

Your bias is showing. If you present your point from a more neutral, matter-of-fact point of view you will have much more success persuading viewers to consider the issue at hand. Just pointing at something and screaming "BAD!" is not good enough, unless you are aiming for the comedic approach.

Best Wishes In Your Future Endeavors
Me

Immigrant = permanently moving to this place and leaving their home behind.

This isn't rocket science.

textDisplay:
Whoever invented this revisionist distinction between immigrant and expat is full of shit and has no idea what these words really mean. An immigrant is someone who moves to a foreign country with the intention of living there permanently and, generally, becoming a citizen of that country. An expat is someone who goes to a foreign country for a generally specified short-term contract and has no intention or desire to live there permanently or become a citizen. The distinction isn't racial or ethnic. It is based on the person's intentions and duration of stay.

These Asian labourers in Dubai would be classified in my country as Temporary Residents on Work Visas. By contrast, the Indians who live in my street are immigrants because they intended to move here permanently, most are now Australian citizens and they have bought houses here.

textDisplay:
I've noticed a pattern from living in a big city.
The "nice" neighborhoods are consistently right next to "poorer" neighborhoods (within 5-10mins)
A REALLY nice neighborhood is next to a REALLY poor neighborhood.
And if it's out in the countryside, the neighborhoods are all ok, but there's the one thriving city nearby.

Wealth always shifts away from one class of people to a different class, usually the ones in the nicer homes next to you.

Dubai having such insane wealth, but also a huge population of poor individuals is horrifying, but not surprising.

The rich are always banking off the labor of the ones who need to work harder.

textDisplay:
"Expat" is a term used when someone leaves. As an example, if I'm in the UK and some other Brit leaves the UK, from my perspective he emigrates and is therefore an emigrant. The place he goes to will consider him an immigrant, because he immigrated there from their perspective. If I have dealings with him and he indicates that he's likely to go home, I describe him from my perspective, like if I visit his "expat" abode, ie his home that is outside of our shared country of origin. If the people of the country he is now in describe him, again from their perspective he immigrated, so is an immigrant.
Why don't we use the term "emigrant" much? Probably because with the variety of accents we have it would be unclear whether you're saying a person is an immi- or emi-grant. It's already hard enough distinguishing the word "emigrate" from "immigrate" when spoken. "He's an əmigrant" leaves it unclear whether you're saying "he moved here" or "he moved away from here". Important to note, seeing as English renders many vowels into schwas when spoken. Since the people using these terms are the ones not actually travelling, they have to deal with the immigrants more often than the emigrants, so "immigrant" got prioritised. Now we have to say "He ehhhh-migrated" to clarify permanent migration away. Which we literally do when people permanently move away.

On top of that, "expat" tends to imply that someone is living away from their home country for a temporary period, rather than migrating. The reality often ends up more ambivalent, as some expats stay forever and some migrants leave after a while. It used to be that migrants would try to assimilate into a country's culture (eg "become an American" &c) while expats would (on account of intending to stay temporarily) not assimilate, since you're not trying to be Spanish, just trying to get a bit of sun. These days, most permanent migrants don't assimilate either, so it's eroded the difference.

Most of the time, people who leave intimate an intention to return. Your fat bald old Dad goes off to Thailand for a bit after your Mum passes on? Expat. He'll come back eventually. Your cousin goes to live in Spain with other fat Brits? Well seeing as he doesn't actually like Spaniards, he's going to come back when he runs out of money. Expat.

Meanwhile your sister who marries the American guy called Brad and goes off to the US of A? She ehhhmigrated, she's an emigrant. Literally that's the word we used. She married him, she's rearing kids there, she's not coming back. It's actual migration. Now you're doomed to emphasise the "e" in "emigrant" for the rest of your life, so to avoid confusion you just say "she's moved there permanently". She's not an expat, because she's not coming back.

If you read foreign language Wikipedia pages on the term expat, you'll see that some of them note specifically that there is a general usage where you're employed by a company but are sent off to a foreign branch for a while. Like if you work for Apple, and they send you to oversee production in China for 2 years, and you live there for that time, then you're an expat. This is clearly different from immigration. It's the difference between getting a temporary work visa, and trying to apply to become a national with a right of residence.

As for "a word white people came up with", um yeah, we came up with the words in our languages. The fact that for instance Japanese fails with 移住者 to differentiate between "emigrant" and "immigrant" (let alone not having a standard word for "expat") and therefore needs to add another word to signify direction of migration, that's a quirk of their own language. Hurr hurr "移住者 is a word brown people came up with so they can act like all migration is equal in effect".

Obviously not. These words are old , way older than modern sensibilities. Their meanings were set largely in stone usually hundreds of years ago. "White people" (seriously can we stop with this race shit? Europeans never gave a damn about race until like 20 years ago, they cared about ethnicity, like Welsh vs English vs French vs Dutch vs Frisian. We're not Americans, we don't have to adopt their constant racial tensions. Also, "white people"? What, the people of the Urals? Romanians? The Swiss? We all have different languages, some based on Latin and others on Germanic and some mixed between... there isn't a "White people" language dude) started using the term "expatriate" long before anyone had a knee-jerk reaction to the word "immigrant".

textDisplay: To me, it seems that Dubai is "forced capitalism". In other words, there wasn't a true market for Dubai's growth. It was just some very wealthy people throwing money into construction hoping that it would spur more growth. Don't get me wrong, I think Dubai still has potential, especially as the "hub" of the Middle East, even the "New York" of the Middle East if you will, but even New York wasn't forced and always had careful investors and not much competition in terms of demand.  I think the major growth factor that Dubai is up against is simply the instability and inequality in the Middle East. Women are still second class citizens and have barriers to invest. Minorities and investors from Iran, Turkey, Pakistan, or Israel also face challenges. JMHO

textDisplay: Beautiful video and superb explanation. I salute you sir. BUT, please be careful when generalizing. E.g. saying something like "Skyscrapers are a bad idea" and showing a picture of Tokyo (view on Mt. Fuji over Shinjuku) ... is just plain nonsense. Unlike Dubai (who has endless deserts which could be covered with buildings), the Japanese actually do NOT have that much flat space that could be used for buildings. So the only way is UP, as it is in many other small countries (look at Singapore). Or, are you afraid of heights? Or that the skyscraper might collapse during earthquakes? (We have earthquakes in Japan like once a month sometimes even more often... But the japanese also have decades of experience building earthquake-proof (to a degree of course) buildings.)

textDisplay:
If Indian cities complete a big project, comments will be about why there is poverty and why it was necessary to embark on a big project.

If China does something, it will be talking about the lack of quality or the lack of rights in China.

If Arabs make something, it will descend into comments about religious extremism and terrorism.

If Africans make something, they will comment about the destruction of the local culture and flora and fauna.

If Khaleejis make something, they will go on a rant about slavery and sand and heat.

When Americans make something, they call it innovation.

When German's make something, they will call it reliability.

When the Japanese do, they say it's precision.

After reading comments and knowing the amount of truth behind them, one can assume that those people live in an alternate reality.

They seem to think that their cities came to be because of their inherent superiority.

It is sad to try to play their game because that would mean we would be making light of the actual issues that exist here, but sometimes I feel someone should go and dig up every accident and fatality in their construction industry and every unpaid worker in their system and publish it in the front pages of newspapers highlighting the 'treatment of the workers'.

But then, there are issues here that need to be heard. From my time here, I've often seen that the employers who treat blue collar workers terribly are often from the same country as the workers, mostly South Asians treating South Asians badly. Very often, the government has responded to criticisms by passing new laws and regulations quicker than it would under any democratic assembly system.

It will take time for things to be fully alright. This place is a desert, so it isn't going to appeal to everyone.

But yes, I really do feel that most of those Westerners comments are rooted in some sense of superiority.
textOriginal:
If Indian cities complete a big project, comments will be about why there is poverty and why it was necessary to embark on a big project.

If China does something, it will be talking about the lack of quality or the lack of rights in China.

If Arabs make something, it will descend into comments about religious extremism and terrorism.

If Africans make something, they will comment about the destruction of the local culture and flora and fauna.

If Khaleejis make something, they will go on a rant about slavery and sand and heat.

When Americans make something, they call it innovation.

When German's make something, they will call it reliability.

When the Japanese do, they say it's precision.

After reading comments and knowing the amount of truth behind them, one can assume that those people live in an alternate reality.

They seem to think that their cities came to be because of their inherent superiority.

It is sad to try to play their game because that would mean we would be making light of the actual issues that exist here, but sometimes I feel someone should go and dig up every accident and fatality in their construction industry and every unpaid worker in their system and publish it in the front pages of newspapers highlighting the 'treatment of the workers'.

But then, there are issues here that need to be heard. From my time here, I've often seen that the employers who treat blue collar workers terribly are often from the same country as the workers, mostly South Asians treating South Asians badly. Very often, the government has responded to criticisms by passing new laws and regulations quicker than it would under any democratic assembly system.

It will take time for things to be fully alright. This place is a desert, so it isn't going to appeal to everyone.

But yes, I really do feel that most of those Westerners comments are rooted in some sense of superiority.

textDisplay: 8:12 This was kind of an off color remark, and pretty inaccurate. There are some key differences between expatriates and settling immigrants worthy of the distinction if nothing but for valuable analytical purposes. In common usage, the term often refers to professionals, skilled workers, or artists taking positions outside their home country, either independently or sent abroad by their employers. Unlike immigrants, who are people arriving from foreign nations to take up new, permanent residence, expatriates are temporary residents who usually have every intention of returning home after brief periods of residency. People working for multinational corporations, branch offices or subsidiaries, or seasonal employees in industries of tourism or contract work, among other things. Expatriates will often retain legal citizenship in their home country, sometimes work on augmented wages, retain voting rights in their country of origin, file taxes jointly from whatever country they're working in, etc. From the position of a functioning government this is an important distinction, in that you can assume if 'X' company/subsidiary, whatever weren't operating abroad inside your country than perhaps a large bulk of their sojourning employee base would in turn not be settled inside your country, which can impact just about everything from an economic standpoint. Particularly a place like Dubai that outsources so much of their labor into their tourism industry which is such a preeminent facet of their economy. There are no inherent racial connotations to the term unless you elect to perceive it as such. I very much doubt white people are the only demographic that works abroad. Probably not even the largest. Again, just kind of a crass statement that was racially apropos for no real reason.

textDisplay:
I agree with your opinion about Dubai but I wouldn't quote Bertolt Brecht. He was a loyal mouthpiece of communism at a time when that was equal to Stalinism, wrote pacifist pieces like "Mother Courage and her Children" when the Party Line was in favour of sitting still - or calls to fight like "Mrs. Carrar's rifles" (I translated those titles myself, so those works may be known under different titles in the English speaking world) when that was the opportune thing.
It is disputed whether he actually wrote all the works now ascribed to him - the case has been made that part of his œuvre was written by his entourage.
In his old age, he lived a very comfortable privileged life in dirt poor East Germany, driving a custom built convertible in this otherwise very pedestrian country.
After the workers' uprising of June 17th 1953 he wrote a witty poem criticizing the East German government but kept his mouth shut about it and made sure it was only published post-humously so it couldn't hurt him.
I'm not impressed by Bertolt Brecht.

textDisplay:
I taught in Dubai for almost 2 years from 2014-15. It reminded me a LOT of Vegas. All style, no substance. It's completely a façade.

The working conditions of Afghani's, Pakistani's, and Filipino's was pretty much atrocious. They have racial hierarchies in Dubai and certain groups basically only did certain jobs. There were signs that said "No Pakistanis wanted!" etc. Nevermind that the country is still a monarchy/dictatorship with no inclinations for civic duty or democracy on the horizon.

Everything was about/in relation to consumerism, shopping, etc. Many of the tram stops are malls. Most of the restaurants and entertainment centers are connected to malls.

My "American" "school" was insane. Absolutely no HR to speak of. Students attempted to buy tests. The admin would alter their grades to make sure everyone passed. Students would fight, be racist, etc, with no consequences. When I finally had had enough and decided to quit they tried to hold onto my passport. That is as a male, white, American. It wasn't until I went to social media, the Dubai Courts, and the American Consulate that they gave me back my passport and I got the hell out of there. Most of the kids are raised by nannies and have no manners, treat workers like shit, and have no consequences. There was no special education either really because the entire subject is taboo there and tied up with inheritance.

Now, I did meet a ton of great people from all over the world. It was an amazing launching point for travel in the region. And many Emiratis (and their kids) were very warm, generous, and kind people. My employer provided me with an apartment, drove me to and from work, provided healthcare, and paid vacations. It was all tax free as well and I made good money. I had many great nights in Dubai, but eventually it just got old. There's only so many nights of clubbing, so many Friday drunches, weekend beach bars (though I did love Barasti haha), and malls that you can take before you need a break. Madinat Jumeirah was a favorite area of mine, would be cool if all of Dubai was kind of like that.

TL;DR - Check it out for a short vacation, but I don't think you could pay me enough to live there again.
textOriginal:
I taught in Dubai for almost 2 years from 2014-15. It reminded me a LOT of Vegas. All style, no substance. It's completely a façade.

The working conditions of Afghani's, Pakistani's, and Filipino's was pretty much atrocious. They have racial hierarchies in Dubai and certain groups basically only did certain jobs. There were signs that said "No Pakistanis wanted!" etc. Nevermind that the country is still a monarchy/dictatorship with no inclinations for civic duty or democracy on the horizon. 

Everything was about/in relation to consumerism, shopping, etc. Many of the tram stops are malls. Most of the restaurants and entertainment centers are connected to malls. 

My "American" "school" was insane. Absolutely no HR to speak of. Students attempted to buy tests. The admin would alter their grades to make sure everyone passed. Students would fight, be racist, etc, with no consequences. When I finally had had enough and decided to quit they tried to hold onto my passport. That is as a male, white, American. It wasn't until I went to social media, the Dubai Courts, and the American Consulate that they gave me back my passport and I got the hell out of there.  Most of the kids are raised by nannies and have no manners, treat workers like shit, and have no consequences. There was no special education either really because the entire subject is taboo there and tied up with inheritance. 

Now, I did meet a ton of great people from all over the world. It was an amazing launching point for travel in the region. And many Emiratis (and their kids) were very warm, generous, and kind people. My employer provided me with an apartment, drove me to and from work, provided healthcare, and paid vacations. It was all tax free as well and I made good money. I had many great nights in Dubai, but eventually it just got old. There's only so many nights of clubbing, so many Friday drunches, weekend beach bars (though I did love Barasti haha), and malls that you can take before you need a break. Madinat Jumeirah was a favorite area of mine, would be cool if all of Dubai was kind of like that.

TL;DR - Check it out for a short vacation, but I don't think you could pay me enough to live there again.
